Anonymous Wed 25 Mar 2020 03:24:12 No.29178084 Report

>>29177307
Two edits to think about.
Change two of the instances of slowly to a synonym. I'd select #2 & #3, then let the last slowly act as a restatement of the action.
>She innocently stared at him with a her big, brown eyes.
Her big, brown eyes stared back at him innocently. She'd hidden any awareness of wrongdoing.
This has two purposes. It prevents three successive sentences from starting with she, breaks the adverb-verb to remove an extra pronoun, and moves the innocently where it can strengthen the next idea better.

A good start. At worst you've got the core of a scene. Build on the quick snapshot imagery.

Writing past a certain length is a puzzle. Having the willpower to step back and trade the autistic hammer for the autistic drill, if that's the best tool, keeps you fresher than obsessing.

I'll give you an example.
I'm in the middle of a rewrite myself. Number six on this piece. Little of the first two drafts remain.
Over the last week or so I outlined the last third of the story. That finally put me in a corner where I have to solidify the background mythology research I've been doing all along.
I've been hoping that once I integrate the subtext in that the more casual scenes will have a nice undercurrent of tension.
If the reader is versed enough in the mythology, hopefully I'll have them screaming along like when watching a horror movie.
It's not that you don't know already what good and bad things are coming, but the surprise of how.

I'll expand on your prompt
>What does belonging look like?
Why does Anon think that's the solution? Is he Romantic (emotionally based) or Enlightened (empirical)? Are his beliefs in accord with society, or opposed?
>How do you get there?
Is he fighting the powers that be? Is he defending his homelands? Is he forced or volunteering? What gives him hope and what betrays it?
>What prevents you from belonging?
Figure at least one each internal and external reason. Did his past behavior isolate him from society? What was he doing before now? Should they accept him initially and face trials together that forge bonds, or does he have to prove his mettle?

Start answering any of these, and see whether you're leaning toward a plot or character based narrative.
